$content = '{"cluster_mapping_a_primer":{"vid":"801","uid":"1","title":"Cluster Mapping: A Primer","log":"","status":"1","comment":"0","promote":"0","sticky":"0","nid":"801","type":"page","language":"und","created":"1388635013","changed":"1388635013","tnid":"0","translate":"0","revision_timestamp":"1388635013","revision_uid":"1","body":{"und":[{"value":"<p><img src=\\"http:\\/\\/i35.tinypic.com\\/23k8xv.png\\" \\/><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<div>\\r\\n<p>The purpose of the U.S. Cluster Mapping Project is to assemble a detailed picture of the location and performance of industries in the United States, with a special focus on the linkages or externalities across industries that give rise to clusters.&nbsp;Cluster mapping has the objective of creating a dataset on the presence of clusters covering the entire U.S. economy and with comparability across regions. This is done by creating a grouping of narrow industry codes \\u2013 the categories in which statistical data from employment to wages is available \\u2013 into cluster categories, i.e. sets of industries that show significant levels of regional externalities and other linkages.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The raw data for the project are&nbsp;the U.S. Census Bureau\'s&nbsp;<a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.census.gov\\/econ\\/cbp\\/index.html\\" target=\\"_blank\\" title=\\"\\">County Business Patterns<\\/a>&nbsp;(CBP)&nbsp;on employment, establishments, and wages by six-digit&nbsp;<a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.census.gov\\/eos\\/www\\/naics\\/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" title=\\"\\">NAICS<\\/a>&nbsp;code (North American Industry Classification System).&nbsp;In addition, U.S. patents by location of inventor are allocated to industries and clusters using a concordance of technology classifications with these codes. There are also confidentiality limitations, which mean that the actual data are not disclosed for every county and economic area in every industry. Various techniques are used to compensate for missing data.&nbsp;<br \\/>\\r\\n<br \\/>\\r\\nIn the cluster mapping project, all industries in the U.S. economy are separated into \\"traded\\" and \\"local\\" based on the degree of industry dispersion across geographic areas. Traded industries are those that are concentrated in a subset of geographic areas and sell to other regions and nations.&nbsp;Local industries are those present in most if not all geographic areas, are evenly distributed, and hence primarily sell locally.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>If two such industries systematically appear to have high levels of employment in the same geographies, there is an indication that they are linked as part of one cluster category. Our past research has identified 41 such cluster categories (see the&nbsp;<a href=\\"http:\\/\\/clustermapping.us\\/resources\\/research-and-methodology\\/?art_wideid=25&amp;art_widemode=details\\" target=\\"_self\\" title=\\"\\">Porter Base Cluster Definitions<\\/a>&nbsp;for a profile of these categories).<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Research also reveals that some industries have connections to multiple cluster categories. While an industry may be linked primarily to one cluster category, in some regions it may function as part of another.&nbsp;For example, while petroleum refining occurs primarily in the context of clusters of Oil and Gas Products and Services, it also shows strong connection to Chemical Products clusters.&nbsp;This can be the result of technology or other capabilities that have multiple uses. The linkages between cluster categories that are revealed through such industries have been found to be crucial to understanding the process of cluster emergence and regional diversification: new clusters often emerge from existing clusters through such linkages. Data on existing cluster portfolios and on cluster linkages is thus a crucial tool to assess the likelihood of where specific new clusters might emerge and prosper.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The limitations of the cluster mapping are largely driven by the data. Economic data is collected in industry codes that remain much more granular on tracking the industries of the past than the industries of the future. In services, for example, there are relatively few industry codes despite their huge importance in the overall economy and their increasing level of differentiation.&nbsp;Economic data is provided at the level of administratively defined regions, like states or economic areas that do not necessarily match with the geographic scope of specific clusters.<br \\/>\\r\\n<br \\/>\\r\\nCluster mapping is designed to enable systematic comparison across regions. This implies that cluster category definitions are best on average when looking across all regions, not when looking at only one region. The biopharmaceutical cluster in the Boston area, for example, includes a significant share of the legal and financial services present in the region. But while it makes sense to include these numbers for a profile of the Boston biopharmaceutical cluster, a national comparison should cover only those industries that are across all regions systematically linked within biopharmaceuticals.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>For further discussion on clusters, please see the following&nbsp;<a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.isc.hbs.edu\\/econ-clusters.htm\\" target=\\"_blank\\" title=\\"\\">Clusters and Cluster Development<\\/a>&nbsp;page from the&nbsp;Harvard Business School, Institute for Strategy and Competitiveness&nbsp;website.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>An&nbsp;<a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.isc.hbs.edu\\/cmp\\/The_Economic_Perfomance_of_Regions---EXCERPT_ON_METHODOLOGY.pdf\\" target=\\"_blank\\" title=\\"\\">extended discussion of methodology<\\/a>&nbsp;is available.<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n","summary":"","format":"filtered_html","safe_value":"<p><img src=\\"http:\\/\\/i35.tinypic.com\\/23k8xv.png\\" \\/><\\/p>\\n<p>The purpose of the U.S. Cluster Mapping Project is to assemble a detailed picture of the location and performance of industries in the United States, with a specia